Compared to the output of the ls --color=never -laS --group-directories-first,
we find that there are some differences:
  - The owner and group names are different.
  - The spacings are different.
  - The file sizes are different.
  - The first column does not have a "+" in the actual game.
  - The ordering of the lines for usr and rooms are different.

Your job for performing your fake implementation of "ls" will need to do this:
  ls --color=never -laS --group-directories-first | sed -f PA.sedfile

   - Here, PA.sedfile is a program that changes any text that ls gives but
     which differs from the game's observed output.

   - Notes: You must always use the text that ls gives you; you cannot insert
            text of your own if that text was already in the input to sed.

            So, for example, you will observe that the home directory of pokey
	    always has the same text display (unlike the rooms, where you can
	    take or drop objects). But that observation does not allow you to
	    mindlessly just dump out the correct text. No, you have to convert
	    the input coming from ls. Never re-type text that could have been
	    obtained from the input.

            Also note that you cannot assume that your user name is always the
	    same. (You see, the TA will run your code, and the TA will have
	    a different user ID and group name.)


